3. How do you count the number of lines that contain a specific word using wc and grep?
We can use the below command-
Syntax: grep <pattern/word> <filename> | wc -l
ex: In the below example, I wanted to count the lines containing “morning”, so to check I used cat and then I used this command,
grep morning file2.txt | wc -l
 

4. What does this coomand will do----> sudo chgrp <groupname> <file-name>
The above command changes the group ownership of the file to the given group.
for ex: 
-	Step1: In the below example, I am choosing “file2.txt” and as you can see the ownership is given to “root”, so I want to change it
 


-	Step2: I want the ownership to be given to the “user33”
 
-	Step3: I use the following command, to change ownership,
sudo chgrp user33 file2.txt
 
-	Step4: Now we can see below the ownership has been changed to “user33” now
 




